                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc>
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support><p>Llygadwy Stone <term>rejected monument</term> <ref target="https://archwilio.org.uk/">CPAT Regional Historic Environment Record</ref>: <idno type="HER">665</idno></p>
                                    <material type="stone">Unknown</material> 
                                    <objectType key="monument">Pillar</objectType> 
                                    <!--<dimensions unit="m">
                                        <height>unknown</height>
                                        <width>unknown</width>
                                        <depth>unknown</depth>
                                    </dimensions>--></support>
                                <condition>No inscriptions are visible on the stone today. The inscriptions recorded by Macalister were fragmentary as it was assumed that cattle rubbing had removed further letters from the stone. RCAHMW recorded scratches on the stone but these are suggested to be from wire chafing.</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout style="vertical" rend="arris_up">Macalister suggested the presence of an Ogham inscription on the north-west angle of the stone as well as a Roman-letter inscription on the south-face of the stone <q>below the modern socket cut in the middle of the face 1.3m above the ground</q>(Redknap and Lewis 2007, 542). However, he has stated that his suggestion of the presence of the Roman-letter inscription was given <q>without any conviction</q> (MacAlister 1922, 542). If the inscriptions were present, the Ogham likely would have read vertically upwards and the Roman-letter inscription likely would have read vertically downwards but this is uncertain. </layout>                            
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>There is no evidence to indicate how the inscriptions might have been carved, so the execution technique remains <rs type="execution" key="other">unknown</rs>. 
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                    </physDesc>
