            <div type="commentary">
                <p> The stone may have been a lost monastic marker (Morgan 1983) but it has also been suggested that it may be post-medieval due to its smooth sides, function as a rubbing-post and due to evidence of post-medieval quarrying nearby. The Welsh Corpus comments on the name of the stone stating that <q>the name <foreign>Llygadwy</foreign> (earlier <foreign>Llygadyw</foreign>, possibly Llygad Duw, 'eye of God') is derived from a nearby ruin, which appears on OS maps with this name</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 542).</p>
            </div>
